00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.069
What is a Seller’s Disclosure
and Why it’s Important.

00:00:03.662 --> 00:00:07.752
Before you list your home, one of the
most important documents you will complete

00:00:08.212 --> 00:00:09.912
is the Seller’s Disclosure Notice.

00:00:11.350 --> 00:00:15.520
The Seller’s Disclosure is a legal
document required in Texas for most

00:00:15.520 --> 00:00:17.850
previously occupied single-family homes.

00:00:18.449 --> 00:00:19.560
Its purpose is simple.

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:23.990
You are disclosing what you know
about the condition of the property so

00:00:23.990 --> 00:00:25.860
buyers can make an informed decision.

00:00:26.629 --> 00:00:29.899
This form is not a warranty and
it is not a home inspection.

00:00:31.060 --> 00:00:34.789
It is a snapshot of your knowledge
of the home based on your experience

00:00:34.789 --> 00:00:36.370
living there or owning it.

00:00:36.912 --> 00:00:40.592
For buyers, the disclosure helps
identify known issues with things

00:00:40.592 --> 00:00:45.512
like the roof, foundation, plumbing,
electrical systems, or past water damage.

00:00:46.172 --> 00:00:50.682
This information helps buyers understand
the property and avoid surprises later.

00:00:51.275 --> 00:00:53.715
For sellers, the disclosure
is just as important.

00:00:54.255 --> 00:00:57.584
Completing it accurately helps
protect you from future claims

00:00:57.584 --> 00:00:59.455
of fraud or misrepresentation.

00:01:00.344 --> 00:01:04.905
Under Texas law, failing to disclose
known issues can expose you to legal

00:01:04.905 --> 00:01:09.174
liability for hidden defects for up to
four years after the sale has closed.

00:01:09.842 --> 00:01:13.492
The form covers a wide range of
topics, including major systems,

00:01:13.632 --> 00:01:18.572
past flooding or insurance claims,
pest issues, repairs, additions, and

00:01:18.572 --> 00:01:21.752
whether there are any known conditions
that could affect health or safety.

00:01:22.287 --> 00:01:25.437
When filling it out, answer
each question honestly and

00:01:25.437 --> 00:01:27.017
based on your actual knowledge.

00:01:27.537 --> 00:01:30.497
You are not required to
investigate, guess, or disclose

00:01:30.497 --> 00:01:31.927
rumors from prior owners.

00:01:32.437 --> 00:01:36.127
If you do not know the answer,
“Unknown” is an acceptable response.

00:01:36.762 --> 00:01:38.492
A common rule to follow is this.

00:01:39.299 --> 00:01:42.450
Do not overshare, but do not
withhold known information.

00:01:42.549 --> 00:01:44.350
If you know about an issue, disclose it.

00:01:45.699 --> 00:01:49.120
The Seller’s Disclosure must be
delivered before or at the time

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:50.629
the contract goes into effect.

00:01:51.199 --> 00:01:54.540
Providing it late can give the buyer
the right to terminate the contract.

00:01:56.412 --> 00:02:00.462
Taking the time to complete this form
carefully helps set clear expectations,

00:02:00.852 --> 00:02:04.472
builds trust, and protects you
legally throughout the transaction.

